posts.message:
I have decided to give up on automated deployments. Being stuck and
not knowing what to do I looked at the top python projects on
github. One of them use travis's auto deploy feature, and they did
custom scripting not travis's built in deployment pipeline. So for
the foreseeable future we'll keep doing the deployments by hand.

posts.author: Toben Archer
posts.message:
Some quick little fixes. First there was a problem where if you
tried to get messages but had put filters on such that there were
no messages that would be returned, an error would be thrown. I
fixed that by having a simple check before going into the code
that pulls messages out of the inbox.

This came up because some one was trying my sample code exactly as
written without reading what it did. So I also changed the example
code in the README.md file to do more of what you would expect.

Lastly there was a similar bug in the fluent message class. I just
added a try catch around the fetching of the body content to keep
it from erroring out. Technically breaks the zen of python, but
it is good enough for now until a dicission is made on how exactly
to handle such a situation.
posts.title: Fixes for Issue #78

posts.author: Toben Archer
posts.message:
I've turned logging off by default. This comes as a feature request from a
@sven700c but also a realization of how things normally ought run. Since
this library is meant to be used as a building block for other
applications it shouldn't have it's own independant logging system. By
turning logging off by default no log is made. But if the user decides he
wants a log, can create one and then the O365 library will attach to it.

posts.author: Toben Archer
posts.message:
files like "message" and "calendar" and "event" which are or are
potential python libraries that could cause conflict. Not wanting
to import each of these by hand, I created O365.py which imports *
from O365*.py. (not actualy syntax) so now all the various bits of
the python-o365 library can be imported in one go. I will probably
eventually compile these files together into one big file, but
until then, this will help keep things easy to maintain and find.

Also worth note. PRINTING! I can now print from python. I haven't
tested it yet with the all to important PDF, but I'll do that
shortly. I mostly want to get this saved and pushed to git hub so
that I don't loose these important bits of progress. printin' w00t
